  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. The specific penalties for money laundering can vary depending on the amount of money involved, the jurisdiction, and the circumstances of the case, but it is generally treated as a serious criminal offense.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily through the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA) of 1986**. Convictions for money laundering can result in severe penalties, including:\n\n- **Prison sentences**: Up to 20 years per count for most money laundering offenses, and up to 30 years for cases involving terrorism financing.\n- **Fines**: These can be substantial, often reaching hundreds of thousands to millions of dollars, depending on the amount of money laundered.\n- **Asset forfeiture**: The government may seize assets connected to the money laundering activity.\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own laws prohibiting money laundering, and individuals can face charges at both the state and federal levels.\n\nMoney laundering involves knowingly engaging in financial transactions to conceal the origins of illegally obtained money, such as proceeds from drug trafficking, fraud, or other criminal activities. Efforts to combat money laundering are a major focus of law enforcement agencies worldwide.",
